reviewText: I has seen about two minutes of a Fred video on YouTube so I knew he was annoying.  However, I did not factor in just HOW annoying a whole movie would be.  This was a regretful parenting permission, even as a streaming download.  As soon as I put on the movie I wished I had not given in to the request.  Fred's voice can make any adult feel like their head is about to explode, within the first two seconds of hearing it (from any room in the house, no matter how distant!).  This movie isn't just bad, it's excruciating.  Just say "NO" to Fred: The Movie, and reclaim 84 minutes of your family's life.
summary: 84 minute movie is 42x worse than a YouTube video

reviewText: Lucas Cruickshank, the eponymous protagonist of "Fred, the Movie" as a teenager is a boy of irresistibly epicene beauty. It is not often, however, in this madcap movie, that there is much of any real opportunity to appreciate suchlike of his pleasing physical assets, except for the rarest moments of smiling calm. That is because the character Fred is in a state of hyper-active, utter mania almost all of the time, grimacing, bounding about, and screeching seemingly uncontrollably. I can understand how many viewers who have commented on this film detest the entire thing as rubbish. However, if one takes the film on its own farcical terms, it is quite endearing. Lucas Cruikshank, if his voice is anything in reality as it is in the movie in which he plays this crazed fifteen-years-old junior high school boy, has yet, so far as his voice is concerned, to complete puberty, though he looks decidedly adolescent enough. More likely, the youthful actor's voice has undergone sonic manipulation. The kid certainly knows how to do frolic acrobatically, leaping and dancing to unbelievably energetic effect!I watched this oddity in a state of attempted disbelief, having to turn down the volume when Fred/Lucas' screeching became too ear-splitting. Elsewhere there are accounts of the zanily exaggerated antics through which the movie's plot (such as it is) puts Fred, so I won't bother here to do the same. It is not a film that I would want to view often, maybe once or twice more during the length of life left to me. Despite that, this movie has a maniacally energetic, hysterical charm all of its own. Anyway, there are few motion pictures of its kind, beyond those of the likes starring, variously, Abbott and Costello, Jerry Lewis, and the Keystone Cops, or maybe occasionally early Eddie Cantor or Marx Brothers, in the company of some of whom, however, it probably is improper to place Cruikshank; maybe he is no more than a screaming human equivalent of the advertising world's animated "Energizer Bunny". I suspect that "Fred, the Movie" will endure as a "party film" and a delightful kiddies' treat, or simply in a niche for the cinematically bizarre.
summary: A Bizarre, Screechingly Intense Film of Unrestrained Mania

reviewText: As you may already know that this movie is based on a character named Fred Figglehorn created and played by Lucas Cruikshank who has his own youtube channel featuring this character and his overly, hyperactive, high-pitched, chipmunk sounding voiced glory. These youtube vids of Fred are funny, entertaining, and so are his music videos and songs in genereal. These youtube vids of Fred are good and worth watching but this movie on the other hand is the exact opposite."Fred: the movie" has nothing but problems such as bad acting, bad singing, zero percent comedy and none of the charm, humor or high-pitched chipmunk voice that Fred had in his youtube vids. In his youtube videos, he was funny but here he totally isn't, it doesn't even look like Fred enjoys being in this movie considering how bad the comedy and script is. If you truly wish to watch Fred Figglehorn; watch his youtube vids, skip this movie. It is physically painful to watch, its beyond bad. 0/10

reviewText: I've come to realize that you either LOVE Fred or you HATE Fred.  There isn't much inbetween.  This humor isn't for everyone, there's no doubt about that.  My daughter and I adore Fred...he's quirky, annoying, ridiculous, and also endearing and sweet.  It's just plain ridiculous humor, rather like Will Ferrel is for adults, I suppose.  The premise of the movie is his love for a girl who lives next door, and she barely knows his name, but that doesn't stop Fred from making a complete fool of himself.  If you can forget the real world for a bit, if you can let go of what should be and just let yourself laugh, maybe you can survive Fred, and even come to love him as we do.  We have all the Fred movies and each one is funnier than the next, but keep in mind as I said, this is ridiculous humor....his annoying qualities ARE funny and are what make us laugh at him.  It's no different than Ren & Stimpy was in the 1990's.  Disgusting, ridiculous AND funny.

reviewText: Let me give a little background for people who don't know.  Lukas Cruikshank (guy who created and plays FR3D) first did the character in youtube videos.  He had some success with this and was even featured on iCarly...Interesting bit that, FAKE internet personalities featuring a REAL internet personality!The character of Fred is supposed to be manic and annoying.  Some of his bits are funnier than others and it surprised us that the iCarly episode seemed to highlight some of his LEAST funny material.As to the movie, we started it not expecting much and even thinking we might have to stop it if it was too bad.  That said we were pleasantly surprised to find ourselves ALL enjoying ourselves.  There are LOADS of funny bits that also play on real personal, social and psychological experiences.  For an example, Fred doesn't know his father, is a rather weak, shy and awkward person; so he imagines that his father "Father Figglehorn" is a big strong and bold wrestler who will simultaneously give him advice to make him try while also caring and being nurturing.  This character was SURPRISINGLY well played by wrestler John Cena!  There are loads of laugh out loud bits including Fred thinking that Pomerians are squirrels!!If you can watch this movie without being impressed by the talents of this young man than you must be a bitter shell of a person!  The sheer imagination and talent that makes it possible to entertain both adults AND children without getting too silly, nonsensical, lewd or crass is both rare and refreshing.For a SMALL example of this guys talent compare the character of FR3D with D3RF a cool, laid back rocker type!  TOTALLY different guys played well by the same guy.
summary: Oh My Gammit! What's Wrong With You People?

reviewText: When my husband watched this and said the kids would enjoy it, I put it on for the kids.  The first time I saw it, I thought it was annoying and dumb.  My kids loved it, so we watched it again.  The second time, I laughed at a couple of things.  Then I realized the more I watched it, the funnier it got, and now I love this movie.  What were annoying and dumb elements in this movie has turned into the exact reasons why I now watch it over and over--even when the kids are asleep.First, Fred overreacts to everything.  An example is when he sees an Asian family who just moved into Judy's house, he assumes she's been kidnapped by Asian people and calls 911.  Then when he finds out Judy moved, he practically destroys the living room but afterwards, he calmly cleans it all up. Hey, at least he cleans up his messes.Second, he imagines all this stuff of how he's getting even with someone or getting Judy to fall in love with him.  At first, I found these jarring from the flow of the movie, but now they're just hilarious because what he imagines is a lot different from what actually happens.  So the contrast works great, but I think you have to be used to it in order to fully enjoy it.Third, I love the jokes, such as "It's Judy.  She's been kidnapped...by kidnappers."  These are corny but they're also funny. And for some reason, the fact that he thinks a dog is a squirrel is hilarious.  I mean, I know we're supposed to think "boy, is he dumb" but the humor in it is actually clever from a comedic viewpoint.Fourth, in the end, you can't help but root for Fred.  He means well and has an innocent charm about him.  Sure, he's hyper and has the high-pitch voice, but he's got a good heart and wouldn't do anything to hurt anyone.So while I didn't like the movie at all when I first watched it, it grew on me, and the fact that my kids love it and I don't feel like I have to fast forward through objectionable parts (like I do with some movies), I'm very happy we found this movie.  (I didn't watch all the You Tube videos other people commented on in the reviews but will do so now.)
summary: The More I Watch It, The More I Like It

reviewText: I was late into the whole "Fred Phenomenon" until I saw a special about it on tv, and I was hooked! So maybe it's weird for a 28 year old while male to enjoy this movie, but I did! It reminds me of someone I work with! I saw it on tv, so I can imagine it's better on DVD. It's sweet and funny. It's about a high school kid with a high-pitched voice going after the love-of-his-life, and getting caught up in funny situations along the way. I don't find his voice annoying, but others might. The actos is really good with the facial expressions to match what Fred is feeling. If you don't know what Fred is, I suggest some youtube research. I cannot wait to buy this on DVD!
